        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Mix and wrap",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Mix together the flour, oatmeal, suet, sugar, dried fruit, treacle, mixed spice, cinnamon, baking powder, and bicarbonate of soda in a large bowl. Beat in the egg and buttermilk to form a stiff dough. It should hold its shape but not be dry.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Wet a large piece of clean cotton cloth or muslin (about 60 cm square) in boiling water. Wring out and lay flat. Dust the centre generously with plain flour. Place the dumpling mixture in the centre and draw the cloth up around it, gathering it above the dumpling. Tie tightly with string, leaving a little room inside for the pudding to expand.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Boil and dry",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Bring a large pot of water to the boil. Lower the dumpling in using a plate placed at the bottom of the pot to prevent the cloth sticking. Keep the water at a steady simmer with the lid on for 3 hours. Top up with boiling water as needed to keep the dumpling submerged.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Carefully lift the dumpling out. Peel back the cloth slowly: the skin underneath should be dry and dark. Place the dumpling on a baking sheet and put it into a 160°C fan oven for 15 minutes to firm the skin further.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Rest for 15 minutes, then slice and serve with cream or custard. Leftovers can be fried in butter the next day.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Dust the cloth very generously with flour before placing the mixture on it. The flour layer is what creates the skin.",
                "cause": "Not enough flour on the cloth, or the cloth was not tight enough.",
                "symptom": "The skin does not form and the outside is wet"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Keep the water at a steady simmer, not a boil. Check at the 3-hour mark by pressing: the dumpling should feel firm all the way through.",
                "cause": "Water was not kept at a steady simmer, or the dumpling was very large.",
                "symptom": "The dumpling is raw in the middle after 3 hours"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Peel slowly and carefully. If it sticks, wet a corner of the cloth with cold water and ease it away.",
                "cause": "Cloth was not floured enough, or pulled off too quickly.",
                "symptom": "The cloth sticks to the skin when you peel it back"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Clootie dumpling is one of Scotland's great national dishes, associated with Burns Night and Hogmanay but eaten throughout the year. The boiling-in-cloth method predates ovens in domestic kitchens: a fire with a pot was what most Scottish households had, and the dumpling adapted to that reality. It is closely related to the English suet puddings of the same era. Fried leftover clootie dumpling for breakfast the next morning is considered by many to be the better use of the dish.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
